    {
      "id": "000e01a13e17",
      "name": "Daily Bible + Stoic",
      "prompt": "# Daily Bible + Stoic Pairing\n\nFind one Bible verse and one Stoic quote or concept that pair together thematically. They should feel like they're answering the same question from two traditions. Then pose 2-3 probing questions for group reflection.\n\n## Format\n```\n## [Theme or Virtue]\n\n**Scripture:** \"[Verse text]\" \u2014 Book Chapter:Verse (translation)\n\n**Stoic:** \"[Quote or concept]\" \u2014 Author, Work\n\n*[One sentence on why these pair. No preaching. Just the thread.]*\n\n**Reflect:**\n- [Question that presses on application, not comprehension]\n- [Question that creates tension \u2014 is this always true? Where does it break?]\n- [Optional third question if the pairing warrants it]\n```\n\n## Quality Rules\n- **Pairing must click.** If it doesn't feel inevitable, pick a different verse.\n- **Questions probe, don't preach.** \"Where is this hardest for you?\" not \"We should all be more X.\" Create tension. Ask what breaks. Ask when the wisdom is wrong.\n- Vary themes day to day \u2014 courage, patience, humility, anger, death, gratitude, honesty, service, leadership, fear, wealth, silence, endurance, forgiveness, pride, justice, anxiety, ambition, reputation\n- Vary books \u2014 not just Psalms and Matthew. Pull from Proverbs, Ecclesiastes, Job, James, Isaiah, Romans, the minor prophets\n- Vary Stoics \u2014 Marcus Aurelius (Meditations), Seneca (Letters, On the Shortness of Life), Epictetus (Enchiridion, Discourses), Musonius Rufus\n- Avoid overused verses. No John 3:16. No \"memento mori\" every third day.\n- Use actual translations (ESV, NIV, NASB, KJV). Don't paraphrase scripture.\n- Whole thing should be about 2x the length of this prompt's example section.\n\n## Schedule\nDeliver daily at 14:00 UTC. Check session_search for previous devotionals to avoid repeats.\n",
